fav_activity:I collected the berries and mushrooms, and that is all I did. The quests I accepted and completed all had to do with harvesting mushrooms and berries. I was able to pay my mortgage quickly because of this. For example, I could take two quests, one for harvesting 4 berries and another for 5 berries, and complete them at the same time. I did not do any other activities because I thought they would be any inefficient way to get money. On maybe another run of the game, I would accept quests like converting the berries to jam, since I already had the berries. Instead, I just sold the berries and mushrooms.
difference:I did not feel like there was a huge difference between the two experiences. In both cases, I would click on the quest board multiple times to reset the quests to the ones I wanted

fav_activity:1. Completing quests was my favorite activity. It was because, in theory, I could gain money while doing I needed to do all necessary tasks that I was going to do anyway. I didn't get to do a lot of them because of a bug. Because of it, when I had the "plant x vegetable" quest, if I ever sold/cooked the same vegetable, the counter would decrement and even become negative. So I had to plant twice as many of that vegetable to get that quest. This should be a very easy bug fix. 2.  The options at the shop felt very restrictive. Often times, I wanted to buy some seeds for a recipe, but I had to wait for DAYS to get the seed that I wanted. Slowed down my progression a lottt. 
difference:No, I didn't notice any difference.

fav_activity:I liked to cook.  I didn't feel like I got to experience it a lot because the inventory is incredibly limiting and the art for the recipes was a little difficult to grasp at a glance.  Therefore I started hunting for simpler recipes that only had one or two ingredients.
difference:I had a good idea what the quickest way to make money was.  I tested out farming, but by sticking to berries, berry quests, and berry foods, I was able to reach the goal much faster.

fav_activity:My favorite activity was doing quests but I didn't do much in the game besides that. I felt like I didn't really play the game because I was too focused on getting the 1000 gold to pay off the mortgage. Once I realized the quickest and/or easiest way to get gold was to get quests related to berries/mushrooms, that is all I focused on.
difference:The first experience I felt I was more naive and exploring so I had more fun. The first run, shop inventories and quests refreshed less frequently so I had more time to enjoy the game. The second run, the quests refreshed more frequently which made me feel more rushed and like I had to the quests I identified as the best strategy.

fav_activity:Submit completed quests, since it gave such a big reward. I didn't get to do a lot because it was rare that quests would appear that I could complete with my current recipes/seeds. In my first experience I made the mistake of accepting all the quests right away, but then I was stuck with ones I couldn't complete the whole time.
difference:It was hard to tell. The second experience seemed to really focus on quests to place furniture at first, but then it got more varied in the later days. The second experience seemed to have more varied recipes for sale in the shop, which was frustrating since the seeds for sale were also more varied, and they didn't line up. The first experience I got "lucky" and the shop had a simple berry recipe right away, though it took me a while to realize that was useful.

fav_activity:I enjoyed the loop of harvesting berries and mushrooms, cooking with them and selling the recipe, while accepting and submitting quests related to those tasks. The Day/Night cycle was fast enough that I felt like there was no downtime during this loop.
difference:I felt a difference, partly because I had a better grasp of the mechanics in the second experience, which meant i went in with a plan to pay off the debt; however during the second experience the quests i wanted sometimes didn't appear, which pushed me to engage with gameplay I didnt use during the first experience (such as furniture)

fav_activity:Cooking recipes was fun, but I didn't get to cook a lot of variety. The goal was to pay off the mortgage, and it would have taken a long time to grow a variety of vegetables, buy different recipes, and try to cook them all. It was faster to take the easiest, most repeatable recipe and the quickest quests to complete
difference:Definitely a difference. The first run felt more challenging, because the quest board felt completely random and I had to coordinate with what showed up on the quest board and in the shop since they refreshed so often. The second run was too easy, because after taking a gathering quest once, it kept showing up frequently and was the easiest to fill. There was no incentive to really plant anything or try to complete any other recipes.

fav_activity:I think my favourite activities were harvesting and making recipes to sell. In both experiences, I do think I accepted lots of quests to do both of these things, in addition to placing furniture. In the first experience, I got recipes to make use of my harvesting earlier on, which did make the second experience slightly harder, but I also got a lot of quests about harvesting in the second experience so I was able to do that in the meantime while waiting for a recipe I wanted to show up in the store.
difference:I do feel like I got more quests that were similar to harvesting/making recipes in the second experience. In particular, in the first experience I don't remember seeing the 'make x recipes' very often, but I definitely saw it a few times in the second experience. I also felt like I saw more harvesting quests in the second experience too.

difference:The first experience felt to me like it flowed better. I was selecting quests that were more achievable and still varied from each other. fav_activity:Cooking recipes, especially berry cake because it was cute. I did, berries could be picked daily. The berry cake recipe turned up early in the game in both playthroughs, so I was able to make use of daily berry picking.
difference:Yes. The difference was that in the second playthrough, I had more difficult quests to complete. There were more recipe quests, and I could not choose easier quests like berry and mushroom picking, which were rarer. So it took more time to complete quests in the second one. For this reason, I relied more on selling berry cake in the second playthrough, whereas in the first, I did many more harvesting quests as came up.

fav_activity:I liked completing quests since I could get a lot of money at once for the task. I accepted a lot of quests so I did feel like I got a lot of experience doing it. I eventually found them to be the best way to make money so I ended up relying on them a lot.
difference:In my first experience I heavily focused on buying seeds and primarily using recipes to gain money. I would get the planted foods, make something, then sell them. In my second playthrough I basically didn't do this at all since I found just doing quests to be a much faster way to make money. I only planted what I needed to in a quest and heavily focused on the berry and mushroom quests.
